<HEADLINE>
<P>
MAN WHO KILLED BOY IN PARK SHOOTOUT SENTENCED; CRIME: LARRY DEAN SHAW GETS 20 
YEARS TO LIFE ON THAT CONVICTION AND 14 MORE YEARS IN WOUNDING OF TWO MEN. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THOM MROZEK, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A judge sentenced Larry Dean Shaw to the maximum term in state prison Friday 
for the murder of a 2-year-old boy who was picnicking on Easter Sunday in a 
park where a gang shootout erupted. 
</P>
<P>
 "This obviously was a horrific type of crime," Superior Court Judge John 
Fisher said. "It seems to me this was one of the worst (crimes) in the Valley 
-- if not the entire city -- in 1993." 
</P>
<P>
 A jury convicted Shaw in November of second-degree murder in the death of Ryan 
Brown, who was hit in the back of the head as his mother tried to flee the 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
 Tamara Lee had testified she was trying to grab her son and run as the 
shooting erupted in Encino's Balboa Park following an Easter egg hunt. 
</P>
<P>
 Fisher sentenced Shaw to 20 years to life in prison for the boy's slaying, and 
then added another 14 years and four months for wounding two men during the 
shooting spree. 
</P>
<P>
 According to testimony, Shaw, holding a gun in each hand, took up a position 
behind the car where Ryan Brown was hiding. The evidence indicated Shaw fired 
into the car, striking the boy with a 9-millimeter bullet. At least three other 
people were believed to be firing guns at the time. 
</P>
<P>
 Wounded in the shootout were Damon Napier, 26, of Sherman Oaks, and James 
Wright, 32, of North Hills. 
</P>
<P>
 Shaw, a 32-year-old Van Nuys man with several prior convictions and a history 
of gang activity, attempted to persuade the jury that he was not the man 
witnesses identified as holding two guns during the shootout. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't think it is fair the way I was found guilty," Shaw told the Probation 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
 But Fisher said the evidence was overwhelming that Shaw fired the shots that 
killed Ryan Brown and wounded the two men, one of whom was left paralyzed. 
</P>
<P>
 Police said Shaw's two guns, recovered after a brief car case, had fired at 
least 17 rounds. 
</P>
<P>
 "Based on the horrendous nature of the crime . . . he should serve the maximum 
amount of time under the rules," Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Dist. Atty. Kathleen Cady, who prosecuted the case, agreed and filed 
documents asking prison officials to keep Shaw locked up for the rest of his 
life. "He should never be released back into society," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
